<p>The <b>Scottish crossbill</b> (<i>Loxia scotica</i>) is a small <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Passerine" title="Passerine">passerine</a> <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bird" title="Bird">bird</a> in the <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Finch" title="Finch">finch</a> family <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fringillidae" title="Fringillidae" class="mw-redirect">Fringillidae</a>. It is <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Endemism" title="Endemism">endemic</a> to the <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Caledonian_Forest" title="Caledonian Forest">Caledonian Forests</a> of <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Scotland" title="Scotland">Scotland</a>, and is the only <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vertebrate" title="Vertebrate">vertebrate</a> unique to the <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/United_Kingdom" title="United Kingdom">United Kingdom</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-2" class="reference"><a href="Loxia_scotica#cite_note-2"><span>[</span>2<span>]</span></a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-3" class="reference"><a href="Loxia_scotica#cite_note-3"><span>[</span>3<span>]</span></a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-4" class="reference"><a href="Loxia_scotica#cite_note-4"><span>[</span>4<span>]</span></a></sup> The Scottish crossbill was confirmed as a unique <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Species" title="Species">species</a> in August 2006, on the basis of having a distinctive <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bird_song" title="Bird song" class="mw-redirect">bird song</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-5" class="reference"><a href="Loxia_scotica#cite_note-5"><span>[</span>5<span>]</span></a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-6" class="reference"><a href="Loxia_scotica#cite_note-6"><span>[</span>6<span>]</span></a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-7" class="reference"><a href="Loxia_scotica#cite_note-7"><span>[</span>7<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
<p></p>
<div id="toc" class="toc">
